There are many types of equations that we will learn to solve. In this section we will focus on a linear equation.

\section*{Linear Equation}

A linear equation is an equation in one variable that can be written, where $a$ and $b$ are real numbers and $a \neq 0$, as:
$$a x+b=0$$

To solve a linear equation it is a good idea to have an overall strategy that can be used to solve any linear equation. In the next example, we will give the steps of a general strategy for solving any linear equation. Simplifying each side of the equation as much as possible first makes the rest of the steps easier.

\section*{EXAMPLE 2.2}

\section*{How to Solve a Linear Equation Using a General Strategy}

Solve: $7(n-3)-8=-15$.

\section*{Solution}

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|l|}
\hline Step 1. Simplify each side of the equation as much as possible. & Use the Distributive Property. Notice that each side of the equation is now simplified as much as possible. & $$\begin{aligned}
7(n-3)-8 & =-15 \\
7 n-21-8 & =-15 \\
7 n-29 & =-15
\end{aligned}$$ \\
\hline Step 2. Collect all variable terms on one side of the equation. & Nothing to do-all $n^{\prime}$ s are on the left side. & \\
\hline Step 3. Collect constant terms on the other side of the equation. & \begin{tabular}{l}
To get constants only on the right, add 29 to each side. \\
Simplify.
\end{tabular} & $7 n-29+29=-15+29$
$$7 n=14$$ \\
\hline Step 4. Make the coefficient of the variable term equal to 1. & \begin{tabular}{l}
Divide each side by 7 . \\
Simplify.
\end{tabular} & $$\begin{aligned}
\frac{7 n}{7} & =\frac{14}{7} \\
n & =2
\end{aligned}$$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|l|}
\hline Step 5. Check the solution. & \begin{tabular}{l}
Let $n=2$ \\
Subtract.
\end{tabular} & Check:
$$\begin{aligned}
7(n-3)-8 & =-15 \\
7(2-3)-8 & \stackrel{?}{=}-15 \\
7(-1)-8 & \stackrel{?}{=}-15 \\
-7-8 & \stackrel{?}{=}-15 \\
-15 & =-15
\end{aligned}$$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

TRY IT 2.3 Solve: $2(m-4)+3=-1$.

TRY IT 2.4 Solve: $5(a-3)+5=-10$.

These steps are summarized in the General Strategy for Solving Linear Equations below.

\section*{HOW TO}

Solve linear equations using a general strategy.
Step 1. Simplify each side of the equation as much as possible.
Use the Distributive Property to remove any parentheses.
Combine like terms.
Step 2. Collect all the variable terms on one side of the equation.
Use the Addition or Subtraction Property of Equality.
Step 3. Collect all the constant terms on the other side of the equation.
Use the Addition or Subtraction Property of Equality.
Step 4. Make the coefficient of the variable term equal to 1.
Use the Multiplication or Division Property of Equality.
State the solution to the equation.
Step 5. Check the solution.
Substitute the solution into the original equation to make sure the result is a true statement.

\section*{EXAMPLE 2.3}

Solve: $\frac{2}{3}(3 m-6)=5-m$.

\section*{Solution}
$$\frac{2}{3}(3 m-6)=5-m$$

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline Distribute. & $2 m-4=5-m$ \\
\hline Add $m$ to both sides to get the variables only on the left. & $2 m+m-4=5-m+m$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $3 m-4=5$ \\
\hline Add 4 to both sides to get constants only on the right. & $3 m-4+4=5+4$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $3 m=9$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

Divide both sides by three.
$$\frac{3 m}{3}=\frac{9}{3}$$

Simplify.
$$m=3$$

Check:
$$\frac{2}{3}(3 m-6)=5-m$$

Let $m=3$.
$$\frac{2}{3}(3 \cdot 3-6) \stackrel{?}{=} 5-3$$
$$\frac{2}{3}(9-6) \stackrel{?}{=} 2$$
$$\frac{2}{3}(3) \stackrel{?}{=} 2$$
$$2=2 \checkmark$$

