\section*{2.6}

Solve: $\frac{2}{3}(9 x-12)=8+2 x$.

We can solve equations by getting all the variable terms to either side of the equal sign. By collecting the variable terms on the side where the coefficient of the variable is larger, we avoid working with some negatives. This will be a good strategy when we solve inequalities later in this chapter. It also helps us prevent errors with negatives.

\section*{EXAMPLE 2.4}

Solve: $4(x-1)-2=5(2 x+3)+6$.

\section*{Solution}
$$4(x-1)-2=5(2 x+3)+6$$

Distribute.
$$4 x-4-2=10 x+15+6$$

Combine like terms.
$$4 x-6=10 x+21$$

Subtract $4 x$ from each side to get the variables only on the right since $10>4$.
$$4 x-4 x-6=10 x-4 x+21$$

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline Simplify. & $-6=6 x+21$ \\
\hline Subtract 21 from each side to get the constants on left. & $-6-21=6 x+21-21$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $-27=6 x$ \\
\hline Divide both sides by 6 . & $\frac{-27}{6}=\frac{6 x}{6}$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

Simplify.
$$-\frac{9}{2}=x$$

Check:
$$4(x-1)-2=5(2 x+3)+6$$

Let $x=-\frac{9}{2}$.
$$4\left(-\frac{9}{2}-1\right)-2 \stackrel{?}{=} 5\left(2\left(-\frac{9}{2}\right)+3\right)+6$$
$$4\left(-\frac{11}{2}\right)-2 \stackrel{?}{=} 5(-9+3)+6$$
$$-22-2 \stackrel{?}{=} 5(-6)+6$$
$$-24 \stackrel{?}{=}-30+6$$
$$-24=-24 \checkmark$$

