\section*{Use a Problem Solving Strategy for Word Problems}

Now that we can solve equations, we are ready to apply our new skills to word problems. We will develop a strategy we can use to solve any word problem successfully.

\section*{EXAMPLE 2.14}

Normal yearly snowfall at the local ski resort is 12 inches more than twice the amount it received last season. The normal yearly snowfall is 62 inches. What was the snowfall last season at the ski resort?

\section*{Solution}

Step 1. Read the problem.

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline Step 2. Identify what you are looking for. & What was the snowfall last season? \\
\hline Step 3. Name what we are looking for and choose a variable to represent it. & Let $s=$ the snowfall last season. \\
\hline \begin{tabular}{l}
Step 4. Translate. \\
Restate the problem in one sentence with all the important information.
\end{tabular} & The normal twelve more than snowfall was twice the amount last year \\
\hline Translate into an equation. & $62=2 s+12$ \\
\hline Step 5. Solve the equation. & $62=2 s+12$ \\
\hline Subtract 12 from each side. & $62-12=2 s+12-12$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $50=2 s$ \\
\hline Divide each side by two. & $\frac{50}{2}=\frac{2 \mathrm{~s}}{2}$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $25=s$ \\
\hline \begin{tabular}{l}
Step 6. Check: First, is our answer reasonable? \\
Yes, having 25 inches of snow seems OK. \\
The problem says the normal snowfall is twelve inches more than twice the number of last season. \\
Twice 25 is 50 and 12 more than that is 62.
\end{tabular} & \\
\hline Step 7. Answer the question. & The snowfall last season was 25 inches. \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

