□ TRY IT 2.60 Solve the formula $A=P+P r t$ for $r$.

Sometimes we might be given an equation that is solved for $y$ and need to solve it for $x$, or vice versa. In the following example, we're given an equation with both $x$ and $y$ on the same side and we'll solve it for $y$.

\section*{EXAMPLE 2.31}

Solve the formula $8 x+7 y=15$ for $y$.
( ) Solution

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline We will isolate $y$ on one side of the equation. & $8 x+7 y=15$ \\
\hline Subtract $8 x$ from both sides to isolate the term with $y$. & $8 x-8 x+7 y=15-8 x$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $7 y=15-8 x$ \\
\hline Divide both sides by 7 to make the coefficient of $y$ one. & $\frac{7 y}{7}=\frac{15-8 x}{7}$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $y=\frac{15-8 x}{7}$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
